# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: south-end-grounds
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:south-end-grounds/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:south-end-grounds/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:south-end-grounds/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:south-end-grounds/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:south-end-grounds/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:south-end-grounds/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:south-end-grounds/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-74-harvard-crimson-football-team] The **1873–74 Harvard Crimson football team** represented Harvard University in the 1873 college football season.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-74-harvard-crimson-football-team] The team played only two intercollegiate games, both against the team from McGill University in Cambridge, with one game ending in a Harvard victory and the other ending in a scoreless tie.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-74-harvard-crimson-football-team] The first game was played under Harvard's rules, while the second game played using McGill's rules on May 15, 1874, was the first rugby-style football game played in the United States.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:south-end-grounds/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] McGill football game** was a two-game series between the Harvard Crimson and the McGill Redmen held in Cambridge, Massachusetts, on May 14 and 15, 1874.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] With the first game being played under the Harvard's "Boston game", the second one was the first rugby-style football game played in the United States.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] It used three periods or "games" and ended in a scoreless tie.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Rutgers football game had been played five years earlier (in 1869), but under a variation of England's The Football Association rules, closer to contemporary soccer than American football.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The Boston game rules were developed by the first organized football team, the Oneida Football Club, founded in 1862.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Many of its members went on to found, and play for, the Harvard team.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] On October 20, 1873, representatives from Yale, Columbia, Princeton, and Rutgers met at the Fifth Avenue Hotel in New York City to codify the first set of intercollegiate football rules.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Before this meeting, each school had its own set of rules and games were usually played using the home team's own particular code.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] At this meeting, a list of rules, based more on association football than on rugby football, was drawn up for intercollegiate football games.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] Harvard, which played the Boston game, a version of football that allowed carrying, refused to attend this rules conference and continued to play under its own code.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] While Harvard's voluntary absence from the meeting made it hard for them to schedule games against other American universities, it agreed to a challenge to play McGill University, from Montreal, Canada, in a two-game series.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The McGill team traveled to Cambridge to meet Harvard.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] On May 14, 1874, the first game, played under Boston rules, was dominated by Harvard, which lead 3–0 after only 22 minutes when the game was ended.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The next day, the two teams played under "McGill" rugby rules to a scoreless tie.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The first game featured a round ball instead of a rugby-style oblong ball.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] McGill used a bladder covered by leather instead of a rubber ball as did Harvard, which was much more difficult to kick.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The game drew about 500 attendees, most of whom were students.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] This series of games represents an important milestone in the development of the modern games of Canadian and American football.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] A similar game was played a year later between Harvard and Tufts establishing this as the first game between two American colleges played under rules used in today's version of American football.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] At this time, the try was not used in American football.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] The try would later evolve into the score known as the touchdown.
[src:south-end-grounds/1874-harvard-vs-mcgill-football-game] In late 1874, the Harvard team traveled to Montreal to play McGill in rugby, and won by three tries in front of 2,000 spectators.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] At least in its third edition, the formal name of the park—as indicated by the sign over its entrance gate—was Boston National League Base Ball Park.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] It was located on the northeast corner of Columbus Avenue and Walpole Street (now Saint Cyprian's Place), just southwest of Carter Playground.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Accordingly, it was also known over the years as Walpole Street Grounds; two other names were Union Base-ball Grounds and Boston Baseball Grounds.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The ballpark was across the New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad tracks, to the south, from the eventual site of the Huntington Avenue Grounds, home field of Boston's American League team prior to the building of Fenway Park.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The Boston club was initially known as the "Red Stockings," because four of its key players had come from the famous 1869–1870 barnstorming team known as the Cincinnati Red Stockings and took the nickname with them to Boston.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Over time the team acquired other informal nicknames, such as "Beaneaters," "Red Caps," "Rustlers" and "Doves." This team eventually adopted the official nickname "Braves," just a few years before abandoning South End Grounds.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] With its tight foul lines and expansive center field, like a scaled-down version of the Polo Grounds, it was sometimes said that the South End had no right or left field, only a center field.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] South End Grounds was rebuilt twice during its lifetime, the first time by choice and the second time by necessity.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The first game at the South End Grounds was played on May 16, 1871.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The original stands were small and rectangular, not unlike the seating area at a county fair grounds.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Behind the right field area were residences and other buildings, and a narrow road called Berlin Street.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Columbus Avenue had not yet been extended as far as the ball park.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The Red Stockings dominated the National Association, finishing just two games behind the leaders in 1871, then winning four straight pennants to close out the NA.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] They joined the newly formed National League in 1876 and won three championships over the first 12 NL seasons.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The last game at this version of the grounds came on September 10, 1887.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The ballpark's stands were demolished later that month to make way for a new structure.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The second South End Grounds was opened on May 25, 1888.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Sometimes referred to as the "Grand Pavilion," it consisted of a large double-decker grandstand behind home plate and uncovered stands stretching down the right and left field lines, as well as bleachers in right-center field.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The medieval-style "witch's cap" turrets were a very popular decoration on public seating structures of the 1880s and 1890s.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The ballpark seated 6,800 by one estimate.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] It was the only double-decked baseball stadium ever built in Boston, apart from the rooftop seating which has turned the single-decked Fenway Park into a *de facto* double-deck ballpark.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The stadium was destroyed in the Great Roxbury Fire of May 16, 1894, which began when children started a small fire beneath the right field bleachers, and which spread and destroyed the stadium and 117 other buildings.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] During the rebuilding process, the Bostons played their home games at Congress Street Grounds.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The third South End Grounds was built in 10 weeks on the site of the old stand and opened on July 20, 1894.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Because the previous structure had not been sufficiently insured, there wasn't enough money to rebuild the stands according to its old plans, and a smaller structure was built.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] One result of the fire was a reconfiguration of the buildings and streets in the area.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Berlin Street disappeared, and Columbus Avenue was constructed, running just outside the right field area, replacing wooden buildings that had once stood there.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] Few photographs of this ballpark seem to be in circulation.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] In one sense, the best known photo might be the one showing the opening game of the 1903 World Series, with the Huntington Avenue Grounds in the foreground; and the South End Grounds in the background, its season over, partially hidden by smoke from the rail yards.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] That image can be seen beside this text.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] On September 12, 1911, 44-year-old legend Cy Young pitched the final home game of his career in a Boston uniform at the grounds against the New York Giants and fellow future Baseball Hall of Famer Christy Mathewson.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The Braves, as they had been rechristened in 1912, moved out of the South End Grounds after their game on August 11, 1914, to accommodate larger crowds during the "stretch drive" of the 1914 pennant race.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The team continued to play at Fenway Park until Braves Field was completed during the 1915 season.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] In contrast to the 11-year lifespan of the Huntington Avenue Grounds, the South End Grounds was the National Association / National League club's home for parts of 44 seasons, a longer time span than any subsequent Braves' home fields.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The stadium was demolished after the Braves left.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The former site of the grandstand and the infield is located where Northeastern University's Interdisciplinary Science and Engineering Complex (ISEC) currently stands, between the Columbus Parking Garage and Ruggles Station of the Orange Line of the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] The outfield was located where the garage stands.
[src:south-end-grounds/south-end-grounds] A historical marker commemorating the South End Grounds is located at Ruggles Station.
